  <li id="comment-4420" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=1644#comment-4420"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2006-09-05T04:54:00-04:00">Tuesday, September 5, 2006 at 4:54 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Oh, Anne, that&#8217;s a big question!  There are many factors involved, and their convergence determines the quality of the bread.  I don&#8217;t feel qualified to give you a thorough answer, but I <>can<> say that good French (or French-style) bread depends on many things: the flour used, the type of oven, the yeast used (dried, fresh, or naturally occurring), and more.  I would recommend going to your local bookstore and looking for a specialized baking book &#8211; or two or three!  That&#8217;s your best bet.  <>Bonne chance<>!</p>
    </div>

